      "bodyTr": "Foreign visitors to Korea in the first quarter of this year reached 4.76 million, marking the highest number for a first quarter on record. This represents a 23 percent increase compared to the same period last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed this growth to the global popularity of K-culture. The BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Square last month is believed to have played a significant role. The phenomenon of K-culture serving as a driver for Korean tourism has become increasingly evident in recent years. In a 2024 survey conducted by the Korea Culture and Tourism Institute, the top reason foreign tourists developed interest in Korea was Hallyu content, followed by Korean traditional culture. What is encouraging is that this interest is expanding beyond Seoul to regions with diverse traditional heritage. According to data from the culture ministry, foreign arrivals at provincial airports in the first quarter surged 50 percent compared to the same period last year. A significant portion of tourists using provincial airports then turn their attention to regional tourism. In the first quarter, regional visitation rates among foreign tourists were 34.5 percent, up 3 percentage points from the previous year, while their regional stay duration and card spending increased by 36 percent and 27 percent respectively. While it may be premature to say that the character of foreign tourism to Korea has fundamentally changed, it is certainly encouraging that foreigners are venturing into regions, staying longer, and spending more. President Lee Jae-myung's mention during a cabinet meeting on the 14th of coordinating local residents, small business owners, and tourism activists with government support likely aimed at nurturing this trend. In response, the Ministry of the Interior and Safety proposed establishing public-private tourism councils at the city, county and district levels, while the Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism expressed its intention to support local tourism activists. The direction of public-private cooperation to actively utilize private sector ideas is sound. However, for this to translate into results, efficiency in local administration must be ensured in areas such as transportation, infrastructure and regulations, and political considerations that impede effective decision-making must be excluded. Tourism is now one of the most urgent solutions available to address regional hollowing and the widening gap between the capital and provincial areas, among Korea's most pressing issues. We must seize the opportunity created by the increase in foreign visitors driven by K-culture.",
